{"art": [], "author": [{"email_address": "wgstexas@gmail.com", "first_name": "W. Gardner", "id": 122, "last_name": "Selby", "name_slug": "w-gardner-selby", "on_staff_page": 84, "phone": "", "photo": null, "publication": {"id": 3, "publication_name": "Austin American-Statesman", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/publication/3/"}, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/staffer/122/", "title": "Former PolitiFact Texas editor", "twitter": ""}], "canonical_url": "/texas/statements/2010/jul/05/david-barton/barton-says-two-gop-house-chairs-did-events-helpin/", "edition": {"adkey": "Editions", "advalue": "Texas", "edition": "Texas", "edition_slug": "texas", "has_afterthefact": false, "id": 2, "index_page": false, "meter_name": "The Texas Truth-O-Meter", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/edition/2/"}, "editor": [], "facebook_headline": null, "id": 2003, "in_future": false, "is_pundit": false, "make_public": true, "preview": true, "researcher": [{"email_address": "wgstexas@gmail.com", "first_name": "W. Gardner", "id": 122, "last_name": "Selby", "name_slug": "w-gardner-selby", "on_staff_page": 84, "phone": "", "photo": null, "publication": {"id": 3, "publication_name": "Austin American-Statesman", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/publication/3/"}, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/staffer/122/", "title": "Former PolitiFact Texas editor", "twitter": ""}], "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/statement/2003/", "ruling": {"adkey": "Truth-O-Meter", "advalue": "Half True", "id": 3, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/statementruling/3/", "ruling": "Half-True", "ruling_graphic": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/static.politifact.com/rulings/tom-halftrue.png", "ruling_slug": "half-true"}, "ruling_comments": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">In a letter  distributed June 12 to delegates to the Republican Party of Texas state  convention, David Barton of Aledo depicts allies of Joe Straus of San  Antonio, the GOP speaker of the Texas House, as too likely to help  Democrats.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Among nearly 20 points he raises:  &ldquo;Straus lieutenants (Reps.) Dan Branch and Jim Pitts are helping Ellen  Cohen against her Republican challenger, doing events with her in her  district.&rdquo; Background: Branch and Pitts, supporters of Straus for  speaker, were appointed by him to chair major committees.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">To back his  Branch charge, Barton pointed us to 25 photos posted online in March by  Cohen, a Houston Democrat. The photos, arrayed under the header &ldquo;Higher  Education Forum,&rdquo; include a shot of Branch, R-Dallas, standing at a  lectern in front of a slide headlined &ldquo;Planning For A Budget Shortfall.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Barton later  elaborated in an e-mail: &ldquo;It is not (standard operating procedure) to do  such events in settings in which Republicans help make a single  Democrat look favorable to her constituents -- especially when it is in  the midst of the campaign cycle rather than the policy/legislative  cycle.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Branch and Cohen each told us that Cohen, a  member of the House Higher Education Committee, invited Branch, the  committee chair,</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">to speak to residents at a public forum  on Feb. 25. Branch said whenever a member of the higher education  committee extends such an invitation, he&rsquo;s got to give it consideration,  and that he and Cohen took pains to keep the forum non-political.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">&ldquo;</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">I told her I  didn&rsquo;t think it would be helpful to do it once the general election  process was in place,&rdquo; said Branch. The forum took place before Cohen&rsquo;s  Republican opponent, Sarah Davis, was nominated in the March 2 primary.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">&ldquo;Most  Republicans who understand the facts will realize I did the right  thing,&rdquo; Branch said. He also said he has not endorsed Cohen: &ldquo;I have not  campaigned for her, I have not given her a contribution.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">What of  Republican Pitts helping Cohen? Barton pointed us to a Web post by  Cohen&rsquo;s campaign inviting visitors to a 90-minute &ldquo;Appropriations Forum&rdquo;  on May 6 featuring Pitts, R-Waxahachie, who chairs the House  Appropriations Committee, on which Cohen sits.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Cohen writes  in the Pitts-related post: &ldquo;I respect Chairman Pitts&rsquo; leadership and  value his insights as we are face critical days of current cuts and  budget shortfalls. I appreciate his willingness to travel to Houston and</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">be a part of  this forum.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Pitts told us he might have erred by  agreeing to speak at the forum in an election year. &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t go there  to help Ellen, that wasn&rsquo;t the purpose. But I learned my lesson. I am  going to be very careful. My timing probably should be before a primary,  or even before people file&rdquo; their candidacies in December and early  January before the primaries.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Pitts said Davis&rsquo;s  husband approached him after he spoke to question his remark that &ldquo;Ellen  and I have our hands full next session&rdquo;-- implying Pitts expects Cohen  to win re-election. &ldquo;I did say that; I guess I&rsquo;m guilty,&rdquo; Pitts said.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Kent Adams,  the GOP nominee&rsquo;s husband, later told us he took note of Cohen campaign  signs outside the Pitts&rsquo; engagement and campaign literature at the  Branch event.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Tammi Wallace, Cohen&rsquo;s chief of staff,  said the signs were put up so audience members could find their way in.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Adams said  Cohen campaign workers and campaign literature were at both events.  Wallace said there was no literature as such, though campaign-funded  constituent survey cards were put out</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: line-through;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">and Cohen  campaign staff members attended the forums &ldquo;because the campaign staff  is expected to pitch in and do whatever they need to do to help out.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Would Pitts  accept invitations to speak at forums hosted by Democratic House  incumbents facing Republican challengers this November? &ldquo;I would pass,&rdquo;  Pitts said. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to send the wrong signal. I would go any place  (to speak) but I don&rsquo;t want to do it with a Democrat and I&rsquo;m not going  to do it for any Republican against an incumbent Democrat.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">His rationale:  He&rsquo;ll need the support of members of both parties to advance the next  state budget. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve got to pass a bill,&rdquo; Pitts said.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Are Branch and  Pitts &ldquo;helping&rdquo; Cohen against her GOP opponent by speaking to her  constituents, as Barton claims?</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: line-through;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Adams, Davis&rsquo;s  husband/campaign manager, said that Cohen obviously intended for the GOP  speakers to boost her campaign, but few people turned out for Branch,  he said, and tax talk at Pitts&rsquo; stop was off-putting. &ldquo;They were  inconsequential,&rdquo; he said.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">For her part,  Cohen characterized the appearances by Pitts and Branch as informational  instead of political. &ldquo;The story to me is the fact that two Republican  chairs of committees I serve on willingly agreed to come in and educate  my district,&rdquo; she said.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">What we find: Barton&rsquo;s  statement accurately refers to the GOP House members appearing at  events with Cohen at her invitation, in her district. But the two forums  weren&rsquo;t political rallies--and even her opponent&rsquo;s campaign manager saw  no boon for Cohen.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">We rate Barton&rsquo;s statement Half True.</span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"><br /></span></p>", "ruling_comments_date": "2010-07-02T19:42:24.347534", "ruling_date": "2010-07-05T12:00:00", "ruling_headline": "Barton says two GOP House chairs did events helping Democratic Rep. Ellen Cohen", "ruling_headline_slug": "barton-says-two-gop-house-chairs-did-events-helpin", "ruling_link_text": "Events yes, not political hoedowns", "ruling_state": null, "source_documents": null, "sources": "<p><span id=\"internal-source-marker_0.11507410705932786\" style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">E-mails, David Barton,  Aledo, </span><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06192010_davidbartonresponse.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">initial response  to PolitiFact Texas</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">, and </span><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06262010_davidbartonresponse.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">follow-up</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">, June 19 and 26, 2010</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Open letter, David  Barton, Aledo</span><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06122010_davidbartonletter.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">, &ldquo;Conservative  Growth in Texas: Danger from Within,&rdquo;</span></a><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">distributed at  Republican Party of Texas state convention, Dallas, June 12, 2010</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">Rep. Ellen Cohen, </span><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ellencohen/sets/72157623560855160/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">online photos</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">,</span><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ellencohen/sets/72157623560855160/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">&ldquo;Higher Education  Forum,&rdquo; and campaign Website, press releases, </span><a href=\"http://www.ellencohen.org/2010/04/state-rep-ellen-cohen-to-host-appropriations-forum-may-6/%20\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">&ldquo;State Rep. Ellen  Cohen to Host Appropriations Forum May 6,&rdquo;</span></a><a href=\"http://www.ellencohen.org/2010/04/state-rep-ellen-cohen-to-host-appropriations-forum-may-6/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\"> </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">accessed June 24, 2010</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interview, Kent Adams,  campaign manager, Sarah Davis Texas House campaign, June 24, 2010</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interview, Rep. Ellen  Cohen, June 24, 2010</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interview, Rep. Dan Branch, June 23, 2010</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interview, Rep. Jim  Pitts, June 22, 2010 </span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interviews, Tammi Wallace, Houston, chief of  staff to Rep. Ellen Cohen, June 24 and July 2, 2010</span></p>", "speaker": {"adkey": null, "advalue": null, "barely_true_count": 1, "current_job": "President, Wallbuilders", "false_count": 0, "first_name": "David", "half_true_count": 1, "home_state": "Texas", "id": 498, "last_name": "Barton", "mostly_true_count": 2, "name_slug": "david-barton", "pants_count": 0, "party": {"id": 3, "party": "Republican", "party_slug": "republican", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/party/3/"}, "photo": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/static.politifact.com/politifact/mugs/davidbartonap.jpg", "primary_edition": {"adkey": "Editions", "advalue": "Texas", "edition": "Texas", "edition_slug": "texas", "has_afterthefact": false, "id": 2, "index_page": false, "meter_name": "The Texas Truth-O-Meter", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/edition/2/"}, "promise_meter_cutout": null, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/person/498/", "total_count": 4, "true_count": 0, "website": "http://www.wallbuilders.com/"}, "statement": "<p><span id=\"internal-source-marker_0.11507410705932786\" style=\"font-size: 18pt; font-family: Times New Roman; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Texas state Reps. Dan Branch and Jim Pitts, lieutenants to House Speaker Joe Straus,  &ldquo;are helping Democrat Ellen Cohen against her Republican challenger,  doing events with her in her district.&rdquo;</span></p>", "statement_context": "an open letter", "statement_date": "2010-06-12", "statement_type": {"id": 2, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/statementtype/2/", "statement_type": "Claim", "type_description": "blog post "}, "subject": [{"description": "", "id": 149, "photo": null, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/subject/149/", "subject": "Bipartisanship", "subject_slug": "bipartisanship", "used_in_edition": ["/api/v/2/edition/1/"]}], "target": [], "twitter_headline": null}